{"id":"1805.01688","submitter":"Kay Bogerd","authors":"Kay Bogerd, Rui M. Castro, Remco van der Hofstad","title":"Cliques in rank-1 random graphs: the role of inhomogeneity","comments":"29 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3150/19-BEJ1125","report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the asymptotic behavior of the clique number in rank-1 inhomogeneous\nrandom graphs, where edge probabilities between vertices are roughly\nproportional to the product of their vertex weights. We show that the clique\nnumber is concentrated on at most two consecutive integers, for which we\nprovide an expression. Interestingly, the order of the clique number is\nprimarily determined by the overall edge density, with the inhomogeneity only\naffecting multiplicative constants or adding at most a $\\log\\log(n)$\nmultiplicative factor. For sparse enough graphs the clique number is always\nbounded and the effect of inhomogeneity completely vanishes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 4 May 2018 09:48:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 11 May 2018 11:27:47 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 29 Mar 2019 14:09:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-31"}
